## 1. `/etc/passwd` — User Database File

Every Linux system stores user information in `/etc/passwd`

```bash
cat /etc/passwd
```

### Structure of each line:

```
root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
 $1  $2 $3 $4  $5    $6    $7
```

| Column | Field | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `$1` | username | login name |
| `$2` | password | always `x` (stored in `/etc/shadow`) |
| `$3` | UID | User ID number |
| `$4` | GID | Group ID number |
| `$5` | description | full name or description |
| `$6` | home directory | user's home path |
| `$7` | shell | default shell |

### Why password is always `x`?

Passwords are **encrypted and stored separately** in `/etc/shadow` for security. `/etc/passwd` is readable by everyone, but `/etc/shadow` is restricted!

### User ID (UID) ranges:

| UID Range | Type |
|---|---|
| `0` | root (superuser) |
| `1-999` | system users (daemon, bin, nobody etc) |
| `1000+` | regular human users |

